    <string name="history_1328">1328 Fire and reconstruction</string>
    <string name="history_1328_body">During a fire in Valladolid caused by Alfonso XI\'s troops, the Magdalena Palace monastery was severely damaged. The nuns began its reconstruction thanks to the financial help of Álvaro Nuño Pérez de Monroy.</string>
    <string name="history_1579">1579 Reconstruction of the church and cloister</string>
    <string name="history_579_body">The nuns built the church according to the plans of the Italian master Pietro Palladio. The altarpiece was the work of Gregorio Fernández and the new cloister, of Francisco de Praves. All this was made possible thanks to the donations of abbesses Ana and Isabel de Mendoza.</string>
    <string name="history_1869">1869 Birth of the monastery school</string>
    <string name="history_1869_body">The community of Huelgas Reales opened its own school, welcoming young noble girls from Valladolid as day boarders.</string>
    <string name="history_XX">20th-21st centuries Restoration and modern life</string>
    <string name="history_XX_body">The monastery has been fully restored. The decrease in vocations led to the creation of the Cistercian Lay Fraternity, which keeps the spirit of the Rule of Saint Benedict alive.</string>
    <string name="history_2007">2007 and beyond Leadership and female Congregation</string>
    <string name="history_2007_body">The monastery is part of the Congregation of Castile of the Cistercian Order, active as a female congregation since 2007. The first president abbess was María del Mar Martínez; after her death in 2013, Sister Isabel Vallés Gallego took over. Currently, Sister María manages the monastery and the school.</string>
